{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":33179,"record_hash":"sha256:7c44e6327904738f0b2cb31da2f4ce0b01f2fe92de86ad32e3c900f258bb7171","timestamp":"2026-05-11T18:32:10.638Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Short answer: mostly no for the exchange format, but yes, the spec/docs should be updated if we keep the new scoped APIs as part of GitMeta.\n\nWhat still aligns:\n- We still serialize normal GitMeta trees: targets, keys, strings/lists/sets, tombstones.\n- We still use normal `refs/meta/*` transport.\n- Scoped refs fit existing spec language that “multiple metadata refs may represent different subsets” and the implementation docs already discuss routed destination refs like `refs/meta/local/private`.\n- `MetaEdit`, `set_record`, `get_record`, and atomic list/set updates are implementation/API ergonomics, not spec-level format changes.\n\nThe meaningful spec-sensitive changes are:\n\n1. `MetadataScope` / `serialize_scope` / `materialize_scope`\n   This is basically “manual scoped destination refs.” That is compatible with the model, but it is not currently described as a first-class implementation concept. I’d update the implementation docs, probably around [serialize-filters.md](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/spec/implementation/serialize-filters.md:1), [storage.md](/Users/kiril/src/git-meta/spec/implementation/storage.md:74), and [workflow.md]([REDACTED:entropy].md:139).\n\n2. `meta:local:` must remain impossible to serialize\n   The spec says `meta:local:` is never serialized. If `serialize_scope()` can serialize a scope that matches `meta:local:*`, that is a real deviation. I would fix the implementation to preserve that hard rule rather than update the spec to allow it.\n\n3. No-common-ancestor set merging\n   We changed behavior so overlapping sets can union. That seems right for sets, but the materialization doc currently says overlapping no-common-ancestor keys are remote-wins, while elsewhere it says conflicts resolve by value-type semantics. I’d update the materialization spec to say no-common-ancestor overlaps use per-type merge semantics, with strings being winner-take-one and sets unioning where appropriate.\n\nSo my recommendation: no major exchange-format spec rewrite, but yes, update the spec/docs. The scoped APIs are now real enough that the implementation docs should name them, and the materialization doc should clarify set behavior. Also, before publishing GitMeta, I’d fix `serialize_scope()` to enforce `meta:local:` exclusion.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T18:32:10.638Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}